% MILESTONE 10 — Literature attribution & state of the art  [VERIFIED]
% The reality check. Determines what (if anything) here is novel.

KEY SOURCES.
  • Bakaev & Yehudayoff, "A note on the affine plank conjecture," arXiv:2602.20290
    (2026) — current SOTA.
  • Verreault, survey, arXiv:2203.05540 (2022; Bull. LMS 2026).
  • Chambers & Moullié, arXiv:1604.00456 (2016).
  • Akopyan, Karasev & Petrov, Discrete Comput. Geom. 69 (2023) 311–322.
  • Ambrus, "Appendix: Plank problems" (2010, web note).
  • Gardner, Pacific J. Math 135 (1988) 299 — relative width is affine-invariant.

VERDICTS ON OUR RESULTS.
  1. 1/d bound (our §3)        : KNOWN. Chambers–Moullié 2016 (via John+Bang);
                                 they also get 2/(1+d). Our Brunn–Minkowski proof
                                 is a clean alternative, nothing more.
  2. Ambrus reduction          : KNOWN. Ambrus 2010 (web note, not a journal).
  3. Two-direction theorem     : KNOWN & recent. Akopyan–Karasev–Petrov 2023
                                 (symplectic-invariants proof). Our coupling
                                 proof may be a cleaner alternative — re-proof.
  4. Facet-parallel simplex    : FOLKLORE (barycentric Σλ_i=1); not a citable
                                 named theorem. Hunter = equality cases (full
                                 citation unverified). Our sumset proof is clean
                                 but the result is elementary/known.
  5. Triangle, 3 generic dirs  : OPEN in all d≥2.

STATE OF THE ART (the frontier we are NOT near).
  • Best planar lower bound: Σ rw ≥ 2/(1+√d) ≈ 0.828 (Bakaev–Yehudayoff 2026).
  • Previous: 2/(1+d) = 2/3 in the plane (Chambers–Moullié).
  • Our bounds (1/2 base; 1 in two special regimes) are BELOW the general SOTA
    of 0.828. The special-case sharp "1" results are known (items 3,4).

HONEST CONCLUSION.
  This project re-derived known/folklore results with clean elementary proofs and
  mapped the obstruction. It did NOT advance the frontier. The expert frontier
  (Bakaev–Yehudayoff 2026, 0.828, sophisticated methods) is far ahead of the
  elementary witness-measure / sumset toolkit used here. The draft must be
  positioned as expository at most, or shelved.

NEXT IF CONTINUING SERIOUSLY: read Bakaev–Yehudayoff 2026 to learn the actual
  frontier methods before any further attempt.
